<h3>The Question</h3>
<p>
    The archived design essay asks for a thin <strong>App Shell</strong> (meta-framework, little to no
    dependency) that loads independently-developed <strong>micro-apps</strong> as pages of one SPA — deciding
    on navigation whether the next page loads <strong>in the same SPA</strong> (compatible) or needs a
    <strong>hard refresh</strong> (incompatible), deduping already-loaded bundles — and a Platform-level
    <strong>compatibility map</strong> that surfaces apps worth converting. No design exists yet. Before
    authoring a standard, this survey gathers web-platform and industry prior art per design-first step&nbsp;1
    so the schema reuses established vocabulary instead of coining terms. It grounds the three open forks in
    <a href="/backlog/104-app-shell-compatibility-map/">backlog&nbsp;#104</a>: <strong>home</strong>
    (protocol vs. Plateau product), the <strong>compatibility-chart schema</strong>, and the
    <strong>memory-eviction model</strong>.
</p>

<h3>Recommendation (carried into #104)</h3>
<ol>
    <li><strong>Split the home</strong> — a thin <code>app-shell-compatibility</code> <em>protocol</em> (the
        declared chart each micro-app authors against, owned by
        <a href="/projects/webmanifests/">webmanifests</a> alongside <code>changelog-manifest</code>) plus the
        live map as a <strong>Plateau dashboard</strong> view of the
        <a href="/backlog/092-provider-consumer-graph-platform-manager/">#092</a> graph. Not either/or.</li>
    <li><strong>Declare flat, render rich-computed</strong> — apps declare a <em>flat requirement manifest</em>:
        an npm-<code>peerDependencies</code>-shaped <code>providers</code> block (semver ranges +
        <code>singleton</code>/optional) <strong>plus OSGi-namespaced <code>claims</code></strong> (globals /
        tag-names / routes — the DOM dimension no version-sharing tool models). The map <em>computes</em> a
        browser-compat-data-style support matrix as the rendered view (BCD is curated/computed, never declared),
        with three states (supported / flagged-degraded / unsupported) and an asymmetric skew window
        (shell-newer = forward-compat; shell-older = fail), per Kubernetes' version-skew policy.</li>
    <li><strong>Borrow the Storage eviction model</strong> — best-effort / persistent classes + LRU under a
        mounted-app budget; unmount via lifecycle and keep the bundle cached. A policy dimension (LRU default,
        pin opt-in), not a baked mechanic.</li>
</ol>

<h3>Finding 1 — the gap is <em>coexistence</em> declaration, not "a declared chart"</h3>
<p>
    <strong>Revised after a deep prior-art pass (2026-06-13).</strong> The App Shell architecture and its
    micro-frontend variants are mature, and — correcting this survey's first cut — declared, introspectable
    manifests <em>do</em> exist. <strong>Module Federation 2.0</strong> ships <code>mf-manifest.json</code>
    (machine-readable <code>exposes</code>/<code>shared</code> with <code>requiredVersion</code>/
    <code>singleton</code>/<code>strictVersion</code>) plus a DevTools extension that <em>renders the federated
    dependency graph</em>; <strong>Native Federation</strong> emits <code>remoteEntry.json</code>;
    <strong>Bit</strong> renders a visual dependency graph. But every one of these declares only the
    <em>shared-library-version</em> dimension. <a href="https://single-spa.js.org/docs/recommended-setup/">single-spa</a>
    has no per-app manifest at all (a central import map), and the tools that <em>do</em> solve conflicting
    globals / CSS / tag-names (<strong>qiankun</strong>'s sandbox, <strong>Luigi</strong>'s iframes) do it by
    <em>enforced isolation</em>, never by a declared, mapped contract. So the genuine novelty is narrower and
    sharper: a <strong>declared <em>coexistence</em> contract</strong> — required shell/provider version
    <em>ranges</em> <strong>plus</strong> DOM-level claims (custom-element tag-names, <code>window</code>
    globals, route ownership) — that a Platform statically resolves and renders as a map over the relationship
    graph (<a href="/backlog/092-provider-consumer-graph-platform-manager/">#092</a>).
</p>

<h3>Finding 2 — compatibility = version-range intersection over shared providers</h3>
<p>
    The same-SPA-vs-hard-refresh decision reduces to: can the new page's required provider/shell versions
    coexist with what is already mounted? Three recurring incompatibility sources:
</p>
<ul>
    <li><strong>Shell / Platform API version</strong> — the new app needs shell&nbsp;≥&nbsp;X; the running
        shell is older (the essay's exact scenario).</li>
    <li><strong>Shared-dependency conflict</strong> — two mounted apps demand incompatible singleton versions
        of one provider (Module Federation's <code>strictVersion</code> failure).</li>
    <li><strong>Conflicting globals / side effects</strong> — two apps claim the same global, custom-element
        tag, or route.</li>
</ul>
<p>
    So the chart is not a new registry — it is a <strong>declaration each app contributes to the #092
    graph</strong> plus a resolver that computes coexistence. It is the forward-looking dual of the
    <a href="/protocols/#protocol-changelog-manifest">changelog-manifest</a> protocol: not <em>what changed</em>
    but <em>what I require to run here</em>.
</p>

<h3>Finding 3 — schema prior art: browser-compat-data's support-statement shape</h3>
<p>
    The richest battle-tested compatibility schema on the platform is
    <a href="https://github.com/mdn/browser-compat-data/blob/main/schemas/compat-data-schema.md">MDN
    browser-compat-data (BCD)</a>. Its <code>__compat</code> object has a <code>support</code> map keyed by
    agent, each value a statement with <code>version_added</code> (incl. <strong>ranged</strong>
    <code>"≤50"</code>), <code>version_removed</code>, plus <code>partial_implementation</code>,
    <code>flags</code>, <code>prefix</code> — and a <code>status</code> object
    (<code>experimental</code>/<code>standard_track</code>/<code>deprecated</code>). Transferable:
</p>
<ul>
    <li>Model units as <strong>(provider/shell, version-range)</strong> pairs — BCD's keyed-by-agent shape maps
        onto keyed-by-provider.</li>
    <li>Carry <code>partial_implementation</code>-style nuance — a page can be <em>degraded-compatible</em>
        (runs, but a flagged incompatibility), not just binary; this is the essay's "older shell, flagged on
        the dashboard".</li>
    <li>Carry <strong>status</strong> so the map surfaces apps pinned to dying providers; use semver ranges
        directly (the <code>changelog-manifest</code> vocabulary).</li>
</ul>
<p>
    Two altitudes: a <strong>flat requirement manifest</strong> (declared) vs. a
    <strong>full BCD-style support matrix</strong> (computed). Declare flat; render the matrix.
</p>

<h3>Finding 4 — eviction prior art: the Storage model (best-effort/persistent + LRU)</h3>
<p>
    The essay flags but leaves open: "you cannot load stuff infinitely, even if conflicts are managed." The
    platform already specifies a graceful model worth borrowing — the
    <a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Storage_API/Storage_quotas_and_eviction_criteria">Storage
    API eviction model</a>: two persistence classes (<strong>best-effort</strong>, evictable, default; and
    <strong>persistent</strong>, opt-in, skipped by eviction), with <strong>least-recently-used</strong>
    eviction under a quota. Mapped onto the shell: a mounted micro-app has a persistence class (pin the current
    route / keep-alive; let background pages be evictable), an LRU policy under a mounted-app budget, with
    <strong>unmount = single-spa's <code>unmount</code> lifecycle</strong> (tear down, release global/tag
    claims, keep the bundle cached for fast re-mount). A policy <em>dimension</em>, not a baked mechanic.
</p>

<h3>Finding 5 — there is no native app shell; adapters keep the incompatible set shrinking</h3>
<p>
    No native primitive loads an arbitrary independent app into your SPA — import maps + dynamic
    <code>import()</code> are the substrate, but the lifecycle/routing/eviction frame is userland (single-spa
    fills it). WE's distinctive lever is the essay's <strong>adapters-via-DI</strong> move: convert an old
    setup to the new API <em>without loading the old implementation</em>, because APIs are dependency-injected
    (the constellation's <strong>webinjectors</strong>). That shrinks the incompatible set over time and makes
    "hard refresh" the last resort, not the first response to a version mismatch.
</p>

